<font color="#FF0000">AFTER (SHOCK) THOUGHTS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Apr 22 23:39:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Well, I guess I am feeling a little black right now. I know that many of us lost a lot more than we realized when &quot;it was all over&quot;. For me it was never &quot;over&quot;. <br><br>
How on earth can you rationalize away the pain of seeing whatever it was you were dedicated to preserve go down the drain? You can't. Regardless of the &quot;historical&quot; events that led to the fall of Saigon, and the endless emotionless analyses in the aftermath, the end of the mess was the mess of the end. The continuum of the Vietnam War, which I feel still persists today with the present nasty government of that country, has not yet run its course. The images of Buddhist Monks engaged in self-incineration from the 1950's still push along the time line, and seem as valid today as they were then.<br><br>
None of this is pretty. None of this is nice. But that's just the way it is. 
